In article <33ohmj$j1c@agate.berkeley.edu>,
Steve Pope <spp@bob.eecs.berkeley.edu> wrote:
>> The RSA software calculates a random near prime number, there are
>> billions of these in the range.

>It seems to me that if there are only a billion (2**30) primes in the
>range, then a brute-force search through these should lead to a viable
>attack.

Actually, there are gazillions of suitable prime numbers in the range.  A
gazillion is a very large number.  Much bigger than a billion.  Even bigger
than a trillion, in fact.  Much, much bigger.  So set your fears at rest.

